<section id="docker-dns-settings">
  <h2>Traefik label routing</h2>
  <p>Docker DNS adds opt-in Traefik labels through Unraid's normal Add/Update Container form. It does not run a DNS server or reverse proxy.</p>

  <h3>One-time setup</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Run Traefik v2 or v3 with its standalone Docker provider and appropriately secured Docker API access.</li>
    <li>Set <code>providers.docker.exposedByDefault=false</code>.</li>
    <li>Set <code>providers.docker.useBindPortIP=true</code> so published Unraid ports are used.</li>
    <li>Create a DNS rewrite from <code>*.home.arpa</code> to the address where Traefik accepts requests.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Enable a route</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Open an application's <strong>Add/Update Container</strong> form.</li>
    <li>Enable its <strong>Traefik route</strong>, then verify the hostname and backend port.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Apply</strong>. Unraid persists the labels and performs its normal container update.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="docker-dns-notice">
    <strong>Scope:</strong> The plugin manages only its own HTTP router and service labels. Traefik entrypoints, HTTPS, certificates, middlewares, DNS, Docker API security, and container lifecycle remain user-managed.
  </div>
  <div class="docker-dns-notice">
    <strong>Before uninstalling:</strong> Disable the route and click Apply for every managed container if you want its labels removed. Uninstalling the plugin does not recreate containers or remove existing labels.
  </div>

  <p><a href="https://doc.traefik.io/traefik/reference/install-configuration/providers/docker/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Traefik Docker provider documentation</a></p>
</section>
